  1. Take the function f(x, y, z) = x2 3x + y4 3y + z2 + 10z + cos(xyz). Find the location of the minimum value. Use c(0, 0 ,0) as the initialization location. Try different initialization locations. Can you find different locations for minima? If you see multiple ones, which one seems to be a global minimum?
fm <- function(x) x[1]^2 - 3*x[1] + x[2]^4 - 3*x[2] + x[3]^2 + 10*x[3] + cos(x[1]*x[2]*x[3])

print(optim(c(0,0,0),fm))
$par
[1]  0.9586131  0.7348568 -4.8938219

$value
[1] -29.81218

$counts
function gradient 
     250       NA 

$convergence
[1] 0

$message
NULL

so the location of the minimum value is (0.9586131,0.7348568,-4.8938219)

min_vals <- c()
for (i in seq(-10,10,1)){
  for (j in seq(-10,10,1)){
    for (k in seq(-10,10,1)){
      min_vals <- append(min_vals, optim(c(i,j,k),fm)$value)
    }
  }
}
summary(min_vals)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.

  1. One the interval [1, ] a probability distribution is defined as p(x) = /x(+1) . Given the sample {2, 3, 2.5, 3, 1.6, 1.4, 1.3, 1.8, 1.9, 2.4, 4.6}, find the log-likelihood, and then calculate the maximum likelihood estimate for the parameter . (Hint: the likelihood function will look very similar to what we had in ICA 14, #2)
samp <- c(2, 3, 2.5, 3, 1.6, 1.4, 1.3, 1.8, 1.9, 2.4, 4.6)
log_likelyhood <- function(a) length(sample) * log(a) - (a+1) * sum(log(samp))

optimize(log_likelyhood,c(1,100),maximum = TRUE)
$maximum
[1] 1.000045

$objective
[1] -17.01368

so the max : 1.000045

  1. The beta distribution on the interval 0 < x < 1 has the form Where is the gamma function. The two parameters and are positive constants. Fortunately, you do not need to use this messy expression, since R has a function to express the probability density: p(x) = dbeta(x, alpha, beta)
  1. Take the sample data in D2L called beta_samp.csv. Construct the log-likelihood function using dbeta.
beta_samp <- read.csv('Downloads/beta_samp.csv')
beta_samp

p_x <- function(para) (-1)*sum(log(dbeta(beta_samp$x, para[1],para[2])))
#?dbeta()
  1. Use the optim function in R to find the maximum likelihood estimate for the parameters.
optim(c(1,1),p_x)
$par

$convergence

So alpha = 2.97645 and beta = 4.94619

  1. With the penguins dataset, construct a 99% two-sided confidence interval for the mean value for body mass with the t-distribution. Then do the same for each species individually.
penguin_mass <- penguins$body_mass_g
penguin_mean <- mean(penguin_mass)
penguin_sd <- sd(penguin_mass)
penguin_size <- length(penguin_mass)

LCL <- penguin_mean + penguin_sd/sqrt(length(penguin_mass)) * qt(0.005, penguin_size-1)
UCL <- penguin_mean + penguin_sd/sqrt(length(penguin_mass)) * qt(0.995, penguin_size-1)
print(LCL)
[1] 4089.426
print(UCL)
[1] 4314.083
